{
  "doc_id": "6890",
  "text": "What is the source of the spontaneous, K+-mediated hyperpolarization, if not the delayed rectifier or the I-IPSP? While several K+ currents have inappropriate activation characteristics, voltage dependence, time course, or pharmacology, a likely possibility is ZK(caj, which is activated by Ca*+ influx, has a duration of several hundred milliseconds, and is reduced by Csf [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . This current also is blocked by muscarinic actions of ACh [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] making it a plausible target of NB actions [CITATION_6] . Influx of Ca*+ during rhythmic, \"rebound\" depolarizations (e.g., through low-threshold channels; [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] 1) could activate ZK(caj. The contributions of Ca*+ and Ca*+-activated currents to V,, fluctuations can be tested, for example, by manipulating Ca*+ buffers in the WCR pipette solution.",
